### Types of Authentication 
1. Token Based 
2. Session Based 

1. Token Based Authentication

Instead of asking the user to enter username and password on every request, the server gives the user a token after login.
A token is a unique encrypted string that acts like a temporary digital ID card.
Example token:
eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...
The most common token format is JWT (JSON Web Token).

# Real-Life Example
Think of a movie theater.

Step 1: Buy Ticket
You show your ID and buy a ticket.
ID Verification = Login

Step 2: Receive Ticket
The theater gives you a ticket.
Ticket = Token

Step 3: Enter Different Areas
Whenever staff asks, you show the ticket.
Show Token instead of Login Again
No need to verify your ID every time.

# Authentication Flow - 

User Login -> Server Verifies Credentials -> Server Creates JWT Token -> User Receives Token -> User Sends Token with Every Request -> Server Verifies Token -> Access Granted

# Summary
Token-based authentication is a method where, after successful login, the server generates a token (usually JWT) and sends it to the client. The client includes this token in every request, and the server verifies it before granting access to protected resources. This avoids storing session data on the server and is widely used in modern Node.js APIs.

# Difference 

| Session Authentication         | Token Authentication          |
| ------------------------------ | ----------------------------- |
| Server stores session          | Server does not store session |
| Uses Cookies                   | Uses JWT Token                |
| Less scalable                  | Highly scalable               |
| Common in traditional websites | Common in REST APIs           |
| Session ID stored on server    | Token stored on client        |
